SIMPLE: endeavor
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Endeavor
<hw>En*deav"or</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. &
p. p.</pos> <conjf>Endeavored</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb.
n.</pos> <conjf>Endeavoring</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OE.
<ets>endevor</ets>; pref. <ets>en-</ets> + <ets>dever</ets>,
<ets>devoir</ets>, duty, F. <ets>devoir</ets>: cf. F. <ets>se mettre en
devoir de faire quelque chose</ets> to try to do a thing, to go about
it. See <er>Devoir</er>, <er>Debt</er>.]</ety> <altsp>[Written also
<asp>endeavour</asp>.]</altsp> <def>To exert physical or intellectual
strength for the attainment of; to use efforts to effect; to strive to
achieve or reach; to try; to attempt.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>It is our duty to <qex>endeavor</qex> the recovery of these
beneficial subjects.</q> <rj><qau>Ld. Chatham.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>To endeavor one's self</b></col>, <cd>to exert one's self
strenuously to the fulfillment of a duty.</cd> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>
⟦ldquo⟧A just man that <xex>endeavoreth himself</xex> to leave all
wickedness.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Latimer.</au></rj></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Endeavor</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Endeavor
<hw>En*deav"or</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To exert one's self; to work
for a certain end.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>And such were praised who but <qex>endeavored</qex> well.</q>
<rj><qau>Pope.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<note><p>Usually with an infinitive; as, to <xex>endeavor</xex> to
outstrip an antagonist.⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He had . . . <qex>endeavored</qex> earnestly to do his duty.</q>
<rj><qau>Prescott.</qau></rj></p></note>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- To attempt; try; strive; struggle; essay; aim;
seek.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Endeavor</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Endeavor
<hw>En*deav"or</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Written also
<ets>endeavour</ets>.]</ety> <def>An exertion of physical or
intellectual strength toward the attainment of an object; a systematic
or continuous attempt; an effort; a trial.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>To employ all my <qex>endeavor</qex> to obey you.</q> <rj><qau>Sir
P. Sidney.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>To do one's endeavor</b></col>, <cd>to do one's duty; to
put forth strenuous efforts to attain an object; -- a phrase derived
from the Middle English phrase ⟦ldquo⟧to do one's
<xex>dever</xex>⟦rdquo⟧ (duty).</cd> ⟦ldquo⟧Mr. Prynne proceeded to show
he <xex>had done endeavor</xex> to prepare his answer.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Fuller.</au></rj></cs></p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Essay; trial; effort; exertion. See
<er>Attempt</er>.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Endeavorer</ent>⟦br⟧
